    "created_at": "2015-08-03T16:01:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-08-03T18:03:32Z",
    "body": "I manged to work around this issue in my main process code. \nThe basic idea is that after each specific event (e.g. `maximize`) you get a `resize` event. The `resize` event fires even after Aero Snap actions. So if you save your previous window state and listen to `resize` you can figure out the current window state.\n\nHere's the code:\n\n``` javascript\n// mainWindow - is my main BrowserWindow\n// Replace the call to sendWindowSizeChange with what ever you want to do with that event\n\nvar WND_STATE = {\n    MINIMIZED: 0,\n    NORMAL: 1,\n    MAXIMIZED: 2,\n    FULL_SCREEN: 3\n};\n\n// The initial state of the window\nvar wndState = WND_STATE.NORMAL;\n\nmainWindow.on('resize', function () {\n    var isMaximized = mainWindow.isMaximized();\n    var isMinimized = mainWindow.isMinimized();\n    var isFullScreen = mainWindow.isFullScreen();\n    var state = wndState;\n    if (isMinimized && state !== WND_STATE.MINIMIZED) {\n        wndState = WND_STATE.MINIMIZED;\n        sendWindowSizeChange('minimize');\n    } else if (isFullScreen && state !== WND_STATE.FULL_SCREEN) {\n        wndState = WND_STATE.FULL_SCREEN;\n        sendWindowSizeChange('fullscreen');\n    } else if (isMaximized && state !== WND_STATE.MAXIMIZED) {\n        wndState = WND_STATE.MAXIMIZED;\n        sendWindowSizeChange('maximize');\n    } else if (state !== WND_STATE.NORMAL) {\n        wndState = WND_STATE.NORMAL;\n        sendWindowSizeChange('normal');\n    }\n});\n```\n"
  },
